    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.10-12_0001" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">10</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Feb'y 12" 1920</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr Neihardt.</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am sending you under separate cover a pamphlet including descriptions of the Rosebud Fight by both Mills and Lemly: The former was written long years after the event. Gen. Mills became distinguished as the head of the Mexican Boundary Com-mission, and also made a fortune as the patenter of the woven war cartridge belt. Lieut Lemly's account must have been rewritten some time after the fight, as he includes my name and I did not join Gen'l Crook 
                    
                        <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.10-12_0002"/>
                    
                        <fw type="curatorial">11</fw>
                    
                until a week after the fight. Crook's inspection of the Indian ambuscade was a year later when we made a trip through the country from Fort Washakie to Fort Custer with Gen. Sheridan and others.</p>
                
                <p>I thank you for your kind offer to send me "The Song of Three Friends" and it would give me the greatest pleasure to accept it.</p>
                
                <p>I have read the "Song of Hugh Glass" and now I shall read it again when my attention can be more upon the expression than upon the absorbing narrative.</p>
                
                <p>Early in my career I knew of a case where a sergeant 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.10-12_0003a"/>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">12</fw>
                    
                <unclear>and</unclear> two privates were on a hunting excursion from, I think, Fort Fred. Steele. <unclear>Wyo.</unclear> The Sergt, was attacked by a bear very much as Hugh Glass was mauled. The other two men found the bear, killed him, made a <unclear>travois</unclear> of his skin and brought the Sergeant into the post.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very truly yours</salute>
                    
                    <signed>W.J. Shuyler</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
